approximately 30,000 protesters marched six miles from Belvedere Park to Laguna Park. They were protesting the fact that Chicanos were disproportionately drafted and killed in the Vietnam War but also oppressed at home. As the crowd reached the park, more than 500 politce attacked the marchers, resulting in the arrest of over 200 persons, hundreds of injuries, and 3 deaths.\"\r\n\r\n\"The Chicano Moratorium was the largest antiwar action on the part of any ethnic community in the United States.\"\r\n\r\n\"Closely linked to the Chicano Moratorium is the assassination of Rubén Salazar. Born in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, Salazar was a journalist who became an important voice for social change...Over time, Salazar became increasingly critical of the war and social injustice, and emerged as a key commentator on the Chicana/o movement.\"\r\n\r\n\"After covering the Chicano Moratorium on August 29, Salazar went to the Silver Dollar Café, where he was shot by L.A. county sheriff\'s deputy Tom Wilson. The projectile came from outside the café and hit Salazar in the head. A coroner\'s panel ruled that the killing was a homicide, but Wilson was never brought to trial.\"\r\n\r\n\"Laguna Park\'s name was changed to Ruben Salazar Park in his honor.\"\r\n(Pulido, et.al.)'),(8608,70,2,50,0,'Ruben Salazar Park and Silver Dollar Cafe'),(7567,258,2,41,1,'<p>The Los Angeles Times created the project \"<a title=\"Mapping LA\" href=\"http://projects.latimes.com/mapping-la/neighborhoods/\" target=\"_blank\">Mapping LA</a>\" in continuation of the boundaries drawn in 2009 by the LA Times mapping out 87 boundaries. This is an interactive map that redrew the boundaries from reader feedback based on what they thought their neighborhoods were defined by. An ongoing project.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(7563,304,3,72,0,'992'),(7564,258,2,50,0,'Mapping LA: Neighborhoods'),(7565,258,2,49,0,'Zoning [LCSH]'),(7566,258,2,49,0,'Neighborhoods [LCSH]'),(8259,147,2,49,0,'Signs and signboards [LCSH]'),(7561