 was designed in 1887 by Robert B. Young and was considered the grandest hotel in the city.  In about 1870, this area was the site of a Chinese market.  By the mid-1930\'s, the hotel was in decline.  The O.t. Johnson Corporation owned the Westminster until 1952.  The Westminster is the only historic building to have been razed at the corner of Fourth and Main Streets (Februrary 1960).  Remaining today on the other three corners are the Barclay (Van Nuys) Hotel, the Farmers and Merchants bank, and the San Fernando Building.\"'),(8189,220,2,39,0,'Ruth Wallach, Linda McCann, Dace Taube, Claude Zachary, and Curtis C. Roseman'),(8190,220,2,48,0,'Historic Hotels of Los Angeles'),(8191,220,2,45,0,'Arcadia Publishing'),(8192,220,2,40,0,'2008'),(8197,219,2,45,0,'National Center for Farmworker Health, Inc.'),(8178,222,2,40,0,'2008'),(8177,222,2,45,0,'Arcadia Publishing'),(8175,222,2,39,0,'Ruth Wallach, Linda McCann, Dace Taube, Claude Zachary, and Curtis C. Roseman'),(8176,222,2,48,0,'Historic Hotels of Los Angeles'),(8186,220,2,50,0,'The Westminster Hotel'),(6161,265,3,74,0,'8'),(6162,265,3,75,0,'1'),(6163,265,3,77,0,'a:7:{s:8:\"FileName\";s:36:\"b21cebffe06549c8f20ea99d8f9e9588.jpg\";s:12:\"FileDateTime\";i:1353994920;s:8:\"FileSize\";i:12493;s:8:\"FileType\";i:2;s:8:\"MimeType\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";s:13:\"SectionsFound\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"COMPUTED\";a:4:{s:4:\"html\";s:24:\"width=\"200\" height=\"160\"\";s:6:\"Height\";i:160;s:5:\"Width\";i:200;s:7:\"IsColor\";i:0;}}'),(6164,265,3,76,0,'FileName:b21cebffe06549c8f20ea99d8f9e9588.jpg\nFileDateTime:1353994920\nFileSize:12493\nFileType:2\nMimeType:image/jpeg\nSectionsFound:\nCOMPUTED:\n	html:width=\"200\" height=\"160\"\n	Height:160\n	Width:200\n	IsColor:0\n\n'),(6165,265,3,73,0,'160'),(6166,265,3,72,0,'200'),(8516,264,2,6,0,'http://www.kcet.org/socal/departures/landofsunshine/arts/murals/estrada-courts-mural-to-be-rededicated.html'),(8511,264,2,45,0,'KCET'),(8512,264,2,40,0,'March 8, 2012'),(8513,264,2,37,0,'Ernesto de la Loza')