INSERT INTO `omeka_exhibits` VALUES (3,'Protests, Riots and its Presentations','<p><img src=\"http://oi49.tinypic.com/1zqzj2p.jpg\" alt=\"\" align=\"right\" /></p>\r\n<p>Los Angeles has an extensive history of social turmoil, community organizing and Civil Rights activism. This section will look into the dynamics of discriminatory housing development, police repression, and its effect on the black community in South Central Los Angeles. Also included are events that were instigated by a disproportionate number of casualties in war among people-of-color, and opposition to American expansionism more generally. More contemporary developments that question economic inequalities, political corruption, waning access to public institutions and corporate greed&nbsp;are also included in this survey.</p>\r\n<p>This section concludes with a handful of various tours covering historical landmarks of radical politics across Los Angeles.</p>','',0,1,'default',NULL,'riots-protests-uprisings'),(10,'Urban and Colloquial Signage','<center><img src=\"http://i46.tinypic.com/a59sn5.jpg\" alt=\"\" align=\"right\" /></center>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A cityscape that has absorbed different architectural features into the built environment also accumulates signage &hellip;&nbsp; The features of these signs include their scale and placement as well as the styles and materials from which they are made. Each assumes a reader or viewer, and each has a point of view or tone.&nbsp; Some, like Jewelry Plaza, the Los Angeles cinema sign and Ped Xing, are placed perpendicular to the motion of vehicular and pedestrian traffic; others, like the signs on stores and awnings, are meant to catch the eye from the opposite pavement. By their size and orientation, the signs on the stores and awnings show they are part of a pedestrian landscape, but also part of a city that assumes commercial traffic occurs on foot in local neighborhoods where recognition, rather than visibility, is the crucial function of a sign. The large size of the Los Angeles sign indicates that it marks a destination, not just a local service, because it can be seen from a considerable distance and is legible at a glance within a long and dramatic sightline. By contrast, the signs on the bus are mobile. They are signs circulating in a city whose routes carry demographic codes and significance, rather than creating a sense of place in a fixed location. To function, such signage has to be premised on a model of systems and flows, traffic and circulation.&rdquo;&nbsp;- Johanna Drucker, <em>Species of Espaces and other spurious concepts addressed to reading the invisible features of signs within systems of relations</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;This section looks at histories and reactions of public signage and the development of graffiti in public space in Los Angeles. &nbsp;It examines primarily downtown theaters and hotels, billboards and advertising, and multilingual signage from the turn of the century to look at the urban reflection of Los Angeles culture. &nbsp;The graffiti section looks at typography of Barrio calligraphy from the 1970s that is unique to the city, as well as gang and crew graffiti. &nbsp;Additionally, it considers graffiti as a reaction to the lettered city and it\'s role as a communication medium.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',' Jerry and Sally Romotsky, Sojin Kim, Susan A. Phillips, Johanna Drucker, UCLA Digital Collections, USC Digital Collections, LA Public Library Image Collection',0,1,'default',NULL,'signage-and-typography'),(8,'Murals','<center><img src=\"http://oi50.tinypic.com/15rxt89.jpg\" alt=\"\" align=\"right\" /></center>\r\n<p>Murals in Los Angeles first arose as an expression of many of the racial and ethnic struggles communities have faced, especially those of Mexican heritage. They became a way for these communities to connect with their culture and hometowns as immigrants. Events like the Bracero Workers Program in 1942 and the Chicano Movement of the 1960s have given artists a driving force and motivation in creating these works of art publicly and on such a large scale. In turn, these pieces of work seen throughout the streets and neighborhoods of Los Angeles have provided these communities with windows to express their social and political concerns while simultaneously contributing to the beautification of these areas. Many projects in Los Angeles have utilized murals as a means to beautify the city in hopes of adding aesthetic quality to school grounds and neighborhoods. By understanding the zoning regimes and the history &nbsp;of layout and urban planning of the city, we can further understand the true impact of these beautifcation efforts on the communities in each area, which largely include the Chicano population and others who play a large role in the creation of such murals. In addition, we can hope to understand the depiction of historical-political context within Mexico after the Mexican Revolution reflected in the tension of ethnically driven political concerns in Los Angeles, and see that creating public works of art is never an easy task in the face of society and politics.&nbsp;</p>','',0,1,'default',NULL,'murals');
