INSERT INTO `omeka_items_section_pages` VALUES (474,NULL,49,'','',8),(473,NULL,49,'','',7),(472,NULL,49,'','',6),(471,NULL,49,'','',5),(470,NULL,49,'','',4),(469,NULL,49,'','',3),(468,NULL,49,'','',2),(475,NULL,19,'','',10),(476,NULL,19,'','',11),(477,NULL,19,'','',12),(534,217,53,'<p>Much of the Los Angeles mural scene is rooted in the development of urban Los Angeles, many of which reside in East LA. Prior to the 1900s, much of Los Angeles became occupied by Spanish and Mexican settlers who came to join the \'multicultural-EuroAmerican community\'. <span>In Mexico at the time, the Mexican Revolution of 1910-20 resulted from a tremendous disagreement among the Mexican people over the dictatorship of&nbsp;</span>President Porfirio D&iacute;az<span>, who stayed in office for thirty one years.&nbsp;</span>During the Mexican Revolution, many immigrated to the region to find employment in these railraods and agriculture, as Los Angeles had become a center for agriculture since the 1830s. Eventually, these areas became home to many low-wage workers with the onset of the contruction of railroads.&nbsp;The mass displacement of non-Mexican populations, including the Jewish, Russian, Japenese (because of the internernment), and Chinese pushed the Mexican American community eastward. By the 1930s, East Los Angeles required even more housing to meet the demands of returning servicemen, laborers, and the Bracero workers from Mexico who came to Los Angeles as a distribution point for the rest of California (further discussed on the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/exhibits/show/murals/chicano-history/bracero-program\" target=\"_blank\">next page</a>). The <a href=\"http://estradamurals.humanities.ucla.edu/?page_id=51#_ftn1\" target=\"_blank\">Estrada Courts</a> in East Los Angeles, in particular, became home to these displaced Mexican communities. Many of the murals that were created in these courts were an expressional response to this community formation by Mexican immigrants and laborers at the time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(485,NULL,43,'','',16),(486,NULL,49,'','',9),(487,NULL,49,'','',10),(488,NULL,49,'','',11),(489,NULL,49,'','',12),(490,263,50,'<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Policy:&nbsp;<span>These are depictions of how policy of urban renewal and beautification change over time with the rise of tourism and aesthetic sensibility of the city.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Further reading:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Beautification Lives in the City of Los Angeles\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/106\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Beautification Lives in the City of Los Angeles</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"LA Could Once Again Allow Murals\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/28\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">LA Could Once Again Allow Murals</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"City Celebrates 800th Community Beautification Grant Project\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/114\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">City Celebrates 800th Community Beautification Grant Project</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><br /></span></p>','',1),(491,NULL,50,'','',2),(492,NULL,50,'','',3),(493,NULL,50,'','',4),(494,NULL,50,'','',5),(495,NULL,50,'','',6),(496,NULL,50,'','',7),(497,NULL,50,'','',8),(498,NULL,50,'','',9),(499,259,51,'<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Murals as Art:&nbsp;<span>This section contains documents that record historic shifts in thought about murals in the context of public art, and the subsequent social and cultural implications.&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Muralism now has been adopted by many communities of different ethnic and socio-economic backgrounds as a means of expression. The SPARC Neighborhood Pride program (video featured below) is a prime example of community engagement through the use of muralism and public art to create goodwill within certain neighborhoods, especailly with youth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><span><br /></span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Further Reading:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a title=\"Public Art at the Global Crossroads\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/135\" target=\"_blank\">Public Art at the Global Crossroads: The Politics of Place in 1930s Los Angeles</a></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Murals: Fine, Popular, or Folk Art?\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/136\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Murals: Fine, Popular, or Folk Art?</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Murals in Latino Communities: Social Indicators of Community Strengths\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/37\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Murals in Latino Communities: Social Indicators of Community Strengths</span></a></p>','<p><a title=\"SPARC Neighborhood Pride Mural Program 1988-2003\" href=\"http://youtu.be/hNStgaE5jGQ\" target=\"_blank\">\"SPARC Neighborhood Pride Mural Program 1988-2003\"</a></p>',1),(478,NULL,16,'','',10),(479,NULL,16,'','',11),(480,NULL,16,'','',12),(481,NULL,16,'','',13),(482,NULL,16,'','',14),(483,NULL,16,'','',15),(484,NULL,16,'','',16),(467,258,49,'<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Zoning:&nbsp;A look at how sections of Los Angeles were determined, both racially and physically, with invisible boundaries and also structural and inherent divides.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Since the onset of industrialization, Los Angeles has been undergoing urban restructuring since the 1960\'s that has had significant impact on changing the social, economic, and political geography of the city. The re-defining of boundaries according to spatial geography can be attributed to the restructuring of capital and therefore labor. The dramatic increase of population in Los Angeles from the 1940s-1960s is due in large part to immigration of workers to industrialized LA during World War II - thus creating a decentralization of housing or population, creating less of a concentration in downtown that seemed uncharacteristic of large cities. This rapid spread of low-income housing and social/politcal events caused corporate and government interests in beautification or \"renewal\" programs to boost tourism and capital.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">This constantly changing geography and shifting boundaries of neighborhoods can be seen through the LA Times\' project, Mapping LA. Historically, and even now, redefining boundaries often shifts communities and ethnic groups geographically - thus changing dynamics and the way that art is practiced in their place of residence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;Further reading:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"&quot;Urban Reconstructing: An Analysis of Social and Spatial Change in Los Angeles&quot;\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/14\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Urban Reconstructing: An Analysis of Social and Spatial Change in Los Angeles</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Zoning Los Angeles: a brief history of four regimes\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/13\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Zoning Los Angeles: a brief history of four regimes</span></a></p>','',1),(138,NULL,16,'','',9),(139,34,17,'<p>Arguably the most famous image of the Zoot Suit Riots vitims.&nbsp;</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Zoot Suit Riot Victims</h2>',1),(140,253,17,'<p>\"The events that culminated in the zoot-suit riots of 1943 cannot be traced to only one or two sources. A close examination of the social and political climate of Los Angeles in the early 1940&rsquo;s reveals that a combination of factors was responsible for the riots. All these factors, however, reflect the city&rsquo;s attitude toward minorities in general and, more specifically, the Mexican-American population of Los Angeles.</p>\r\n<p>Fully expecting a sea attack from Japan after Pearl Harbor, military and civilian authorities in Los Angeles took a hard look at the activities of all minorities in the city. First, all Japanese were moved inland, away from the shoreline. This fear of subversive activities among the Japanese was extended to all minorities by a series of books that were widely read and discussed by people in Los Angeles in 1943. The paranoia generated by books such as Martin Dies&rsquo;s The Trojan Horse in America (1940) and Harold Lavine&rsquo;s Fifth Column in America (1940) led to the creation by the California State legislature of a joint senate-assembly committee to investigate communist, fascist, Nazi, and other foreign-dominated groups. The Mexican-American community became one of the objects of this growing fear of foreigners in 1942, when the Joint Fact-Finding Committee on Un-American Activities in California launched an investigation of the Sinarquistas, an anti-Communist society that had tried to influence politics in Mexico and was charged with perpetrating subversive activities in the barrios of Los Angeles. The hearings of this committee, which continued from 1940 until 1945, contributed to the city&rsquo;s xenophobic response to the Mexican-American community during the entire decade.\" &ndash; eNotes.com Zoot Suit Riots</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Zoot Suits Lined Up</h2>',2),(141,252,17,'<p>\"The Zoot Suit Riots occurred in Los Angeles between June 3rd and June 13th, 1943. They are a remarkable event in that they defy simple classification. They were not about zoot-suiters rioting, and they were not, in any conventional sense of the word, &ldquo;riots.&rdquo; No one was killed. No one sustained massive injuries. Property damage was slight. No major or minor judicial decisions stemmed from the riots. There was no pattern to arrests. Convictions were few and highly discretionary. There were no political manifestos or heros originating from the riots, although later on the riots would assume political significance for a different generation. What the riots lack in hard incriminating evidence, they make up for in a plethora of emotions, fantasies, and symbols.\" &ndash; Mauricio Maz&oacute;n, The zoot-suit riots: the psychology of symbolic annihilation</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Violence of the Zoot Suit Riots</h2>',3),(142,251,17,'<p>This is an example of what the actual zoot suits looked like. The distinctive outfit is still looked at a vital piece to Los Angele\'s culture.&nbsp;</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Zoot Suit Outfits</h2>',4),(143,254,17,'<p>\"In August 1942 the murder of a young Mexican-American man ignited a firestorm in the City of the Angels. In no time at all, ethnic and racial tensions that had been building up over the years boiled over. Police fanned out across the city in a dragnet that netted 600 Mexican Americans. Among those accused of murder was a young \"zoot-suiter\" named Hank Leyvas -- the poster boy for an entire generation of rebellious Mexican kids who refused to play by the old rules. As he and sixteen other boys headed to trial, the mood of the city turned violent. The deck was stacked against the defendants, and a verdict of guilty would spark a series of brutal riots. The convictions were ultimately overturned, but the city and its inhabitants would be forever changed.\"&nbsp;(http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/zoot/eng_filmmore/index.html)</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Zoot Suit Riots Documentary</h2>',5),(144,NULL,17,'','',6),(145,NULL,17,'','',7),(146,NULL,17,'','',8),(147,NULL,17,'','',9),(148,70,18,'<p>Ruben Salazar, who was an LA Times journalist instrumental in articulating Chicano struggles around the time of the Chicano Moratorium, was assassinated in the Silver Dollar Cafe by a sheriff\'s deputy\'s after just having reported on the anti-Vietnam Chicano movement in Laguna Park</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Ruben Salazar Park and Silver Dollar Cafe</h2>',1),(149,115,18,'<p>The Chicano Movement of the 1960s in LA&nbsp;was a response to the discrepancies between the promises of American justice and the lived realities of minorities in California.&nbsp;</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">\"\'&iexcl;Mi Raza Primero!\'(My People First!): Nationalism, Identity, and Insurgency in the Chicano Movement in Los Angeles Book Review\"</h2>',2),(150,255,18,'<p>\"The Chicano Moratorium marches against the Vietnam War played a decisive role in ending that conflict\" (http://www.latinopov.com/blog/?p=6011)</p>\r\n<p>\"In an eye-opening study, political science professor Dr. Ralph Guzman found that from 1961 to 1967, Mexican Americans made up 19.4 percent of U.S. casualties in Vietnam from Southwestern states even though they represented only 10% of the overall population in these states. Something was clearly wrong. By 1970, Chicano anti-war activists were speaking out publicly that Chicanos were being used as cannon fodder.\"(http://latinopia.com/latino-history/1970-national-chicano-moratorium/)</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Vietnam War and the Chicano Moratorium</h2>',3),(151,256,18,'<div id=\"dublin-core-description\" class=\"element\">\r\n<div class=\"element-text\">\"The philosophers have only interpreted the world, in various ways: the point, however, is to change it.\"<br />(Marx: Theses on Feuerbach)</div>\r\n</div>','<p>Working Class Uprising</p>',4),(152,257,18,'<p><span>\"On August 29, 1970, a \"Chicano Moratorium\" against the war in Vietnam was held in East L.A. Loyola-Marymount film student Tom Myrdahl shot this documentary, capturing the events that unfolded as law enforcement and protesters clashed in and around Laguna Park. This film has not been seen in nearly 40 years. Tom, who is still a working cameraman in Los Angeles, is putting this historic film on the web as a tribute to the brave citizens of East L.A. who came together 40 years ago to voice their dissent against the Vietnam War.</span><span>\" (Youtube)</span></p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Chicano Moratorium Documentary</h2>',5),(153,NULL,18,'','',6),(154,NULL,18,'','',7),(155,NULL,18,'','',8),(156,NULL,18,'','',9),(137,NULL,16,'','',8),(136,192,16,'<p>\"<span>Residential segregation and white violence in South L.A. were facilitated by unabashed police violence. Consequently, no account of South L.A. would be complete without acknowledging the powerful role of police brutality, and resistance to it, in shaping life in this part of the city</span>\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">White police officer surveys slain Black man</h2>',7),(135,180,16,'<p>\"The incident that is credited to starting the 1965 Watts Riot involved Marquette and Ronald Frye who on August 11, 1965 were stopped by a police officer for erratic driving.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">\"Attorney A. L. Wirin with Rena Frye and her sons, Ronald and Marquette at Los Angeles courthouse, 1965\"</h2>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>',6),(134,153,16,'<p>\"You&rsquo;ve got some Gestapo tactics being practiced by the police department in this country against 20 million black people, second class citizens, day in and day out &ndash; not only down South but up North. Los Angeles isn&rsquo;t down South. Los Angeles isn&rsquo;t in Mississippi. Los Angeles is in the state of California, which produced Earl Warren, the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court &ndash; and Richard Nixon, the man who was Vice President of this country for some eight years and who wants to run for president again.\" - Malcom X<br /><br />Malcom X a year before the riots, is ironically holding up a newspaper saying \"we must have justice.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Malcolm X in Los Angeles 1964</h2>',5),(133,154,16,'<p>\"Local blacks who drove through the war zone gave the pass sign, one finger meant you were from Watts, two meant Compton and three meant neighboring Willowbrook. Anyone not hip to this code risked a serious beating or even death.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">I\'m a Blood Brother Poster</h2>',4),(132,155,16,'<p>\"Local residents frolic in the shadows of the Watts towers. Built between 1921-54 by immigrant Sam Rodia, he named them &ldquo;Nuestro Pueblo&rdquo; meaning &ldquo;Our Town.&rdquo; For Rodia, the Towers were a gift to his adopted country, an artistic symbol of peace. The closeness that \"Our Town\" implied back in Sam Rodia&rsquo;s day would quickly dissolve amidst the ever changing postwar world. The economic boom that hit Los Angeles after WWII would drastically alter the ethnic make up of Watts.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Watts Towers in 1965</h2>',3),(131,13,16,'<p><span>\"This article explains how, through tools of land-use regulation, several groups of actors became particularly adept at shaping the form of Los Angeles and to what ends. In Los Angeles, there have been distinct winners and losers, and these winners and losers have varied over time. In Los Angeles, there seem to be four distinct regimes characterizing the historical politics of land use. Rampant speculation defined the first, lasting from the advent of zoning in Los Angeles in 1921 into the Depression, government-sponsored big real estate the second, lasting from the Depression until the 1960s, and anti-growth advocates the third, lasting from the 1960s until 2000, with the fourth forming over the last decade and characterized by a balance between allied housing and development interests and anti-growth advocates. This article documents the rise and fall of these regimes and summarizes their varying impacts on the city.\"</span></p>','<h2 class=\"title\">\"Zoning Los Angeles: a brief history of four regimes\"</h2>',2),(130,72,16,'<p>\"Before World War II, South L.A.\'s working-class neighborhoods were racially segregated by an invisible barrier known as the \"White Wall\" along Alameda Boulevard. African Americans lived to the west of Alameda, whites to the east.</p>\r\n<p>During the Watts uprising in 1965, Alameda emerged as racial dividing line...Many whites fled South Los Angeles immediately after the Watts uprising, citing Black violence and fears of school integration, and taking advantage of racially exclusive housing in the suburbs.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">The \"White Wall\", South Central Incinerator, and South Central Farm</h2>',1),(523,NULL,36,'','',10),(524,NULL,36,'','',11),(525,NULL,36,'','',12),(526,NULL,36,'','',13),(527,NULL,36,'','',14),(528,NULL,36,'','',15),(529,NULL,36,'','',16),(530,NULL,33,'','',9),(531,NULL,33,'','',10),(532,NULL,33,'','',11),(533,NULL,33,'','',12),(173,11,19,'<p>\"The article examines the state of race relations in Los Angeles, California a decade after the riots of April 1992 that resulted in 55 deaths and over $1 billion in property damage.\"</p>','<h2>\"America\'s Urban Crisis a Decade After the Los Angeles Riots\"</h2>',1),(174,158,19,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Rodney King, We Love You My Brother Graffiti</h2>',2),(175,157,19,'<p>The Aftermath of the Riots. The community is using graffiti as a mechanism to convey their opinion on the police.</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">F*** the Police Graffiti</h2>',3),(176,156,19,'<p>\"May 2, 1992: People march calling for peace during the Los Angeles Riots in Koreatown.\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">The American Dream? We Want Peace</h2>',4),(177,150,19,'<p>A public remembrance of the police brutality endured by Rodney King and the tragic killing of the youthful LaTasha Harlins.</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Graffiti Commemorating Rodney King and LaTasha Harlins</h2>',5),(178,NULL,19,'','',6),(179,NULL,19,'','',7),(180,NULL,19,'','',8),(181,NULL,19,'','',9),(540,NULL,53,'','',7),(541,NULL,53,'','',8),(542,NULL,53,'','',9),(543,NULL,53,'','',10),(544,NULL,53,'','',11),(545,NULL,53,'','',12),(535,218,53,'','',2),(536,219,53,'','',3),(537,131,53,'','',4),(538,NULL,53,'','',5),(539,NULL,53,'','',6),(194,50,22,'<p>In response to the recent eruption of Occupy Wall Street on September 17th, 2011, several hundred students and activists converged on Wilson Plaza on November 17th in order to address critical issues concerning higher education, namely burgeoning student debt, skyrocketing tuition costs, and lack of student governance over university function to name a few. Students and workers alike, alumnus, faculty articulated their concerns over the direction and affordability of and access to the university.</p>\r\n<p>Going into the night, approximately 40 students and community members decided to Occupy--against school ordinances--Wilson Plaza. Early the next morning, protesters met no less than 100 police actors at the site of occupation, and were demanded to evacuate or else risk arrest. 14 activists ended up being arrested for charges of unlawful assembly and failure to disperse, which sparked the already burning debate within the community over what constitutes a space for free assembly and speech, and, more generally, to what extent do we control--not just \'own\'--our university.</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Wilson Plaza Occupation</h2>',1),(195,51,22,'<p>\"Occuparty\" was both an act of solidarity and direct response to the then recent indiscriminate <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WmJmmnMkuEM\" target=\"_blank\">pepper spraying of UC Davis students by university police</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=buovLQ9qyWQ\" target=\"_self\">police brutality occurring on the UC Berkeley campus</a>. Occurring on the same night as the university-nationalist \"USC Bonfire\" rivalry party, Occuparty decided to parody these tropes of competition by presenting itself as the real enemy of the standing university. Ritualistically covered up for the week preceding the cross-town rivalry football game against USC, the Bruin Bear\'s encasement became subject to student and community messages deriding the governments lack of attention to the university population. The banner questioning \"Public or Private?\" spanned the protective box, along with other statements like \"End Apathy\", \"Cut military spending-rebuild America\", and \"Prop 13\" written inside of a crossed out circle.</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Occuparty at Bruin Plaza</h2>',2),(196,49,22,'<p>&ldquo;Eleven people were arrested and protesters shut down Wilshire Boulevard for two and a half hours Wednesday afternoon in the loudest pushback against tuition hikes and state budget cuts near UCLA since 2009.</p>\r\n<p>The protest was linked to a broader day of action across the state of California, organized through a group called the ReFund California Coalition. The group has emerged in the wake of the Occupy protests and adopted refunding public education as its core concern.</p>\r\n<p>At least seven of those arrested identified themselves as UCLA students.&rdquo;<br />Daily Bruin 11-10-11</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">ReFund California Coalition Rally</h2>',3),(197,NULL,22,'','',4),(198,NULL,22,'','',5),(199,NULL,22,'','',6),(200,NULL,22,'','',7),(201,NULL,22,'','',8),(202,NULL,22,'','',9),(419,168,45,'<p><img src=\"http://www.museumsyndicate.com/images/artists/647.jpg\" alt=\"Siqueiros\" width=\"98%\" /></p>\r\n<p>Chicano murals were inspired largely in part by the mural movement that started in Mexico after the Mexican Revolution. The government started the movement to promote the ideals of the Mexican Revolution, thus incorporating many aspects of political narrative within the murals themselves. From this time rose \"Los Tres Grandes,\" or rather the fathers of muralism who would shape and influence Chicano muralism within Los Angeles. These artists were Diego Rivera, David Alafaro Siquerios, and Jos&eacute; Clemente Orozoco. Ultimately, the goal of their work was to create a statement or enforce certain ideals that were very historically rooted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Further Reading:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Mexican Muralism: Its Social-Educative Roles in Latin America and the United States\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/260\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">\"Mexican Muralism: Its Social-Educative Roles in Latin America and the United States\"&nbsp;</span></a></p>','',1),(418,115,44,'<p><span>Social movements have always provided muralists and painters with a rich iconography to choose from.&nbsp;The Chicano Movement encompassed a broad cross section of issues&mdash;from restoration of land grants, to farm workers\' rights, to enhanced education, to voting and political rights, as well as emerging awareness of collective history.<span>&nbsp;Prior to the 1960s, however, Latinos lacked influence in the national political arena.&nbsp;</span></span>Like other movements of the era, Chicanismo, the affirmation of Mexican American culture and a rejection of assimilation, was&nbsp;a product of youthful idealism and energy. It responded to the discrepancy between promises of American justice and prosperity and the&nbsp;lived reality of minority peoples.&nbsp;<span>&nbsp;Socially, the Chicano Movement addressed what it perceived to be negative ethnic stereotypes&nbsp;of Mexicans in mass media and the American consciousness.</span></p>\r\n<p>In the heady days of the late 1960s, when the student movement was active around the globe, the Chicano movement brought about more or less spontaneous actions, such as the mass walkouts by high school students for quality of education in Denver and&nbsp;<a>East Los Angeles&nbsp;i</a>n 1968 and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=Chicano+Moratorium\">Chicano Moratorium</a>&nbsp;in Los Angeles in 1970.&nbsp;<span>Community issues like unemployment, housing, food, and education became important elements in their agenda. Not only did the publication of the newspaper, La Causa, by Eleazar Risco and the Brown Berets helped to bring awareness of the problems faced every day in the barrios of East L.A., but murals and public artwork later resulted from these sociopolitical struggles to also bring awareness and express angst.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Further rescources:</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/117\">The Dialectics of Repression: The Los Angeles Police Department and the Chicano Movement, 1968-1971</a></p>\r\n<p><span><br /></span></p>','',1),(546,105,52,'<p>This piece analyzes the effects of the election and what the artist believes as that America\'s youth is going to be in trouble either way. Both Obama and Romney are clearly shooting a little kid in a mickey mouse hat portraying the government is destroying the youth in America.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(547,109,52,'<p>Thrashbird made this right outside of a voting booth. It brings up the controversy of whether he was going too far.</p>','',2),(548,121,52,'<p>The artist portrays Romney as a villianous character giving a huge influence to the community of their opinion of the Republican presidential candidate.&nbsp;</p>','',3),(549,NULL,52,'','',4),(550,NULL,52,'','',5),(551,NULL,52,'','',6),(552,NULL,52,'','',7),(553,NULL,52,'','',8),(300,247,33,'<p>At the turn of the 20th century downtown Los Angeles was a hub for theaters, movie palaces, and vaudeville acts. Main St. had the most dense population of nickelodeons and theaters, although the only historic buildings that remain today are the Regent and the Merced. When the Pantages and Orpheum theaters opened on Broadway in 1910 it became the most popular part of LA nightlife. The decline of spectacular theater architecture began in the 1920s when the business and entertainment sectors moved from downtown to Hollywood.</p>\r\n<p>The Lyceum theater opened as the Los Angeles Theater in 1888, becoming the second location of the Orpheum in 1903. In 1911 the Orpheum moved to it\'s current location on Broadway, and the theater became Fischer\'s Lyceum which played movies until it\'s demolition in 1941.</p>\r\n<p>Excerpt from an LA Times column by Lee Shippey, November 1930:</p>\r\n<p>\"The new theater on Broadway between Sixth and Seventh is to be called the Los Angeles Theater, and the announcement says \'It is the first theater to be named in honor of the city\'.</p>\r\n<p>Jay Hunt, veteran actor, writes us that \'in 1890, my wife and I appeared in the Los Angeles Theater on Spring Street, the same that is now called the Lyceum and is a picture house. Maude Granger, then a very popular actress, was the star. Harry Wyatt was manager of the theater at that time. We played a three-night engagement, but changed the bill every night because the city then wasn\'t big enough to provide more than one good audience for each play.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>It is clear from this 1919 photograph of the Lyceum that signage played an important role in distinguishing theaters from surrounding buildings as well as successfully promoting their current productions. &nbsp;The front of the theater is stylized and, in addition to repetitive and frequent advertising, has public photographic displays of actors and performers. &nbsp;</p>',1),(301,227,33,'<p>The Roxie Theater was the last to be built on Broadway in 1932. &nbsp;The theater was meant to be used for film, however during the construction a stagehouse was included - a sign of the evolving entertainment industry in LA. &nbsp;Noted for its Art Deco style, including its stepped roofline, angular grillwork, chevron ornament, and terrazzo sunburst, the theater\'s flat architecture stands out from the crowded street.</p>','',2),(302,145,33,'','<p>By 1965 this area of skid row near Broadway is described as \"a haven for alcoholics\". &nbsp;Neon signs for bars, hotels, restaurants, and theaters compete for attention of passersbys in cars.</p>',3),(303,245,33,'<p>\"There was a time, long ago, when the streets of downtown Los Angeles were awash in neon&mdash;thanks to a confluence of movie theaters the world had never seen before. Dozens of theaters screened Hollywood\'s latest fare, played host to star-studded premieres and were filled nightly with thousands of moviegoers. In those days, before World War II, downtown L.A. was the movie capital of the world.\"</p>\r\n<p>In 2006, the Los Angeles Times wrote: \"Of all of L.A.\'s many hidden gems, maybe noe is as sparkling nor as hidden as the Broadway theater district downtown.\" Bemoaning the possible loss of such gem, the same writer noted: \"L.A. gave birth to the movies. To lose the astonishing nurseries where the medium grew up would be tragic.\"</p>','<p><img src=\"http://i50.tinypic.com/54armv.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>',4),(304,220,33,'<p>As the population of Los Angeles grew rapidly and business and theater venues began expanding into major streets like Main, Sprint, Broadway, and Hill. &nbsp;Hotels in downtown LA were built to accommodate the demands of a growing hub of local economy and entertainment. &nbsp;For the first half of the 20th century hotels primarily catered to tourists, business travelers, and residents. &nbsp;The customer base moved to people from international business and other industries, including presidents, international diplomats, leaders, of industry, movie stars, and celebrities.</p>\r\n<p>The Westminster was designed in 1887 by Robert B. Young and was considered the grandest hotel in the city at the time. &nbsp;Before it was built, the location was a site of Chinese market. &nbsp;By the 1930s, when Downtown Los Angeles was awash with lit signs for hotels and theaters, the Westminster was in decline. &nbsp;The entrance to the building, located at Fourth and Main Streets, has little signage or indication of function.&nbsp;</p>','<p>The Westminster Hotel</p>',5),(305,221,33,'<p>The U.S. Hotel was built in 1863, the cities third hotel. &nbsp;The hotel boasted \"best two-bit meal in Southern California\", according to ads published in issues of Los Angeles Times at the time. &nbsp;The signage for this hotel rises above the store fronts below it, the use of flat space for billing and advertising is ideal in order to distinguish the facade and is legible from further away. &nbsp;</p>','<p>The U.S. Hotel</p>',6),(306,222,33,'<p>The U.S. Hotel was demolished in 1939 in order to be replaced with more modern building. &nbsp;The Herald Examiner captioned this a \"gaunt ghost of bygone gaiety of the early days of Los Angeles\".</p>','<p>Demolition of the U.S. Hotel</p>',7),(307,NULL,33,'','',8),(308,35,34,'<p><em>Click image below then click title to play video:</em></p>\r\n<center><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/262\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://i43.photobucket.com/albums/e377/stephNme2/Screenshot2012-11-14at102830PM.png\" alt=\"\" /></a></center>\r\n<p>As you can see on the left, many murals throughout Los Aneles were the creation of Mexican American artists as an expression of the angst and upheaval during the Chicano (Civil Rights) Movement (El Movimiento Chicano) in Los Angeles that started during the 1940s. <em>Am&eacute;rica Tropical </em>had virtually been forgotten after being white washed until the start of the Chicano Art Movement in 1962.&nbsp;<span>During the 1960\'s an important component of the Chicano Movement was the involvement of artists in this socio-political movement. As artists began to actively participate in the efforts to redress the plight of Mexicans in the United States, there emerged a new iconography and symbolic language which not only articulated the movement, but became the core of a Chicano cultural renaissance.These murals were a way to resist models of Anglo assimilation and instead affirm Chicano narratives. It became a process of self-definiton of the Chicano community in Los Angeles. Their approach was collective in spirit and took from the context of the Chicano Civil Rights Movement. These artists mapped another L.A. as a part of social protest and community empowerment movement.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Further Resources:</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/159\" target=\"_blank\">Chicano Art Organization</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/160\" target=\"_blank\">Fowler Museum Chicano Art Exhibit</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>David Alfaro Siqueiros, one of the great Mexican artists of the 20th century, painted&nbsp;<em>Am&eacute;rica Tropical</em>&nbsp;in 1932 on the second story exterior wall of the Italian Hall on Olvera&nbsp;Street, in the area of downtown Los Angeles known as El Pueblo.&nbsp;It was a representation of the oppression of the indigenous worker by imperialists.The context didn&rsquo;t go over well with those running the city at the time and the mural was white-washed, painted over.&nbsp;In the 1970s, while social turmoil gave rise to the Chicano movement, that mural began to bleed through its white curtain.&nbsp;The story behind it includes an art movement of epic proportions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span><span>It\'s been more than 35 years since Chicano art grew out of the political urgency of the Chicano civil rights movement. The earliest examples of the work were aesthetically raw posters and banners inspired by the farmworkers\' struggle and by protests over social issues in cities throughout the Southwest. It quickly grew into a more refined body of work that often was marked by familiar religious and cultural images--La Virgen de Guadalupe, Day of the Dead skeletons, pre-Columbian figures, lowriders. The genre, dominated by narrative paintings and lush palettes, took its place as a distinct movement in the American art scene. Los Angeles--by virtue of its role as one of Mexican America\'s most important capitals, and the sheer number of artists working here--became the center of the Chicano art universe.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><br /></span></span></p>\r\n<p><br /> <object id=\"flashObj\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,47,0\" width=\"280\" height=\"70\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1&amp;isUI=1\" /><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /><param name=\"flashVars\" value=\"videoId=1876166309001&amp;playerID=1701167444001&amp;playerKey=AQ~~,AAABaiKAEyE~,k8IxH-zHxokz1F4AWHWplnUBlrRNTGRw&amp;domain=embed&amp;dynamicStreaming=true\" /><param name=\"base\" value=\"http://admin.brightcove.com\" /><param name=\"seamlesstabbing\" value=\"false\" /><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"swLiveConnect\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\" /></object></p>',1),(309,NULL,34,'','',2),(310,NULL,34,'','',3),(311,NULL,34,'','',4),(312,NULL,34,'','',5),(313,NULL,34,'','',6),(314,NULL,34,'','',7),(315,NULL,34,'','',8),(316,204,35,'<p>The development of advertising in Los Angeles goes hand and hand with the development of the automobile (Drucker). &nbsp;The increasing amount of billboards and advertisements seen in the public sphere since the turn of the 20th century has been stalled but not stopped by more recent legislation. &nbsp;The Hollywood sign was originally built for $21,000 in 1923 for a new housing development called Hollywoodland. &nbsp;Described by the developers as a neighborhood of \"superb environemnt without excessive cost on the Hollywood side of the hills, the sign has since come to represent the lifestyle of wealth and priviledge that is associated with living in the Hollywood hills.</p>\r\n<p>The original Hollywoodland sign including 50-foot letters and four thousand 20-watt light bulbs. &nbsp;The sign, which was built as a temporary structure, deteriorated until 1949 when the \'land\' was removed. &nbsp;The Hollywood Chamber of Commerce discontinued the use of light bulbs because the Parks Department demanded they finance the costs themselves. &nbsp;By the 70s the sign was in disrepair - no longer a representation of the prospering Los Angeles of the last half century. &nbsp;The sign was replaced through private donation in 1978 and the letters were replaced with more permanent steel frames. &nbsp;</p>','<p>The rebuilt Hollywood sign</p>',1),(317,230,35,'','<p>This 1935 photograph of the Broadway tunnel includes neon signage and billboards for Carnation, California Prunes, M-J-B Coffee</p>',2),(318,233,35,'<p>The large expansion of public advertising in Los Angeles is due in part to the lack of regulation. &nbsp;The March 1929 the&nbsp;<em>California Law Review</em>&nbsp;published an article on \"Billboard Regulation and the Aesthetic Viewpoint with Reference to Caliofornia Highways\":&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"What legislation has been enacted in California on the subject[?] Hardly any. This state prohibits the placing or maintenance of signs on property of the state or its subdivisions &ldquo;without lawful permission,&rdquo; or on private property without the consent of the owner or lessee, and the signs so prohibited are declared to be nuisances. A sign erected upon or over a state road or highway without a permit from the department of engineering is further declared to be a public nuisance, punishable as a misdemeanor. This is all the legislation on the subject in this state.\"</p>\r\n<p><span><br /></span></p>','<p>Billboards in the front yard of a Wilshire Ave. residence&nbsp;</p>',3),(319,207,35,'<p>Members of the City Council of the City of Los Angeles v. Taxpayers for Vincent, 1978</p>\r\n<p><span>\"Section 28.04 of the Los Angeles Municipal Code prohibits the posting of signs on public property. Appellee Taxpayers for Vincent, a group of supporters of a candidate for election to the Los Angeles City Council, entered into a contract with appellee Candidates\' Outdoor Graphics Service (COGS) to fabricate and post signs with the candidate\'s name on them. COGS produced cardboard signs and attached them to utility pole crosswires at various locations. Acting under &sect;&nbsp;28.04, city employees routinely removed all posters (including the COGS signs) attached to utility poles and similar objects covered by the ordinance.\" - Cornell Law</span></p>','<p>By 1975 the Sunset Strip\'s billboards \"primarily tout cigarets [sic] and whiskey in a subdued manner\"&nbsp;</p>',4),(320,NULL,35,'','',5),(321,NULL,35,'','',6),(322,234,35,'<p>In the 1980s the performer Angelyne became an icon by financing billboard space for self-advertisement. &nbsp;These signs make the celebrity into a product, a precursor to the 21st century phenomenon of \"being famous for being famous\". &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Additional reading:&nbsp;Chapter 1 of <a href=\"http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=OWNLM_1u-r8C&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PR9&amp;dq=angelyne+billboards+los+angeles&amp;ots=fk5tVmn7WQ&amp;sig=i-pXCUt6Si8tvJOIhb96RdglqqY#v=onepage&amp;q=angelyne%20billboards%20los%20angeles&amp;f=false\">Claims to Fame: Celebrity in Contemporary America by Joshua Gamson</a>)</p>','',7),(323,261,35,'<p>It is a timeline which shows the history of Los Angeles Billboards, with a focus on the conflicts between Los Angeles citizens, political parties and billboard companies caused by the overwhelming number of billboards in the city which leads to public nuisance. The LA City Council implemented a few regulations which ban supergraphic billboards, and reduce the number of billboards on the streets.</p>','',8),(324,NULL,35,'','',9),(325,NULL,35,'','',10),(326,NULL,35,'','',11),(327,NULL,35,'','',12),(328,NULL,35,'','',13),(329,NULL,35,'','',14),(330,NULL,35,'','',15),(331,NULL,35,'','',16),(349,NULL,38,'','',9),(348,NULL,38,'','',8),(347,NULL,38,'','',7),(346,NULL,38,'','',6),(345,152,38,'<p>Often graffiti interacts directly or indirectly with signage and advertising in the immediate urban environment. &nbsp;In this case, graffiti has been adopted as logotype in these store front signs on Melrose Ave. &nbsp;The graffiti association with hip hop culture in Los Angeles is utilized to brand an idea of style.</p>','<p>Graffiti Appropriated as Commercial Signage&nbsp;</p>',5),(344,151,38,'<p>The perceived relationship between gang tagging and minority communities in Los Angeles has prompted aggressive anti-graffiti and beautification measures. &nbsp;This anti-graffiti graffiti signage, whether meant to be ironic or not, questions the motives behind these programs and ideologies. &nbsp;For more, see the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=beautification\">beautification</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/exhibits/show/murals/urban-beautification-policy\">policy</a>&nbsp;sections.</p>','<p>Graffiti as Anti-Graffiti&nbsp;</p>',4),(343,150,38,'<p>Graffiti can interact and react with signage in the visual landscape to change and create new meanings. &nbsp;This commemoration of Rodney King and the 1992 civil unrest covers an advertisement for an attorney of law and creates a temporal snapshot of cultural tensions. &nbsp;Graffiti as a remix medium creates a colloquial signage that allows a reciprocal narrative between people and their environment. &nbsp;</p>','<p>Graffiti Commemorating Rodney King and LaTasha Harlins</p>',3),(342,63,38,'<p>Referred to as roll calls, this graffiti lists the names of associated gang members of a neighborhood or street in order to publicly signify their ownership of the area and intention to defend it. &nbsp;In her book Wallbangin\': Graffiti and Gangs, Susan A. Phillips applies the same distinctions to Los Angeles Graffiti as Ley and Cybriwsky\'s in their 1974 analysis of Philadelphia gangs; categorizing roll calls as \"positive statements about group belonging and membership\". &nbsp;</p>','<p>Roll Call in Old English Lettering</p>',2),(341,149,38,'<p>The stylized barrio graffiti unique to Los Angeles chicano neighborhoods are referred to as \"<em>mi plaqueso</em>\" - \"my sign\". &nbsp;The placas are meant to be illegible to outsiders while explicitly operating as a public personal advertisement within the barrios, as well as \"disclosing the values and concerns of young barrio residents (Romotsky)\". &nbsp;An inscription of one of more names without an explicit gang or neighborhood affiliation is seen as non-threatening \"calling-card\".</p>','<p>The Plaqueaso of Norm Azusa 13</p>',1),(350,NULL,38,'','',10),(351,NULL,38,'','',11),(352,NULL,38,'','',12),(353,NULL,38,'','',13),(354,NULL,38,'','',14),(355,NULL,38,'','',15),(356,NULL,38,'','',16),(357,169,39,'<p>Point lettering, one of the oldest and most respected barrio alphabets, follows the similar line work as Old English forms. &nbsp;While Point lettering changes curves into angles both follow many of the same typographical conventions. &nbsp;Old English lettering dates back to Gutenberg\'s&nbsp;press, however, unlike typesetting tags are inscribed by hand and can not be reproduced in the same way.</p>\r\n<p>\"This comparison of Old English letters with a Point lettered plaqueaso illustrates the similarities of the two forms. &nbsp;Jesse, written in a thin stroke, approximates the directions of the Old English or Gothic lower case letters, derived from an essay Albrecht Durer wrote and illustrated in 1535 (Romotosky).\"</p>','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Comparison of Point Lettering to Old English</p>',1),(358,170,39,'<p>This is an example of a plaqueaso superimposed over Durer\'s Old English alphabet. &nbsp;The close stylistic lettering of Robin\'s R to Durer\'s demonstrates the similarities in point lettering to Old English. &nbsp;</p>','<p>Robin\'s Plaqueaso Superimposed over Old English Lettering</p>',2),(359,171,39,'<p>Point alphabets similarly adopt the idea of character decoration seen in Old English typesetting, despite whether or not it impacts the legibility of the plaqueaso. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"What the Point lettering achieves in lieu of legibility is both a decorative strength and an aura of exclusivity (Romotsky).\"</p>','<p>Example of Sharp Point Lettering</p>',3),(360,172,39,'<p>Loop lettering appears less often because of it\'s difficulty to execute. \"The Loop alphabets feature an S-curve looping around a straight line of each letter so that one part of the letter contains a shape resembling the figure eight (Romotsky).\" Loop lettering is often stylized into Square or Point looped lettering.</p>','<p>El Blackbird in Continous Loop Lettering</p>',4),(361,173,39,'<p>Block lettering emphasizes a blocked and thick aesthetic as opposed to the thin angles of Point letters. &nbsp;Block letters are often outlined and three dimensional shapes. &nbsp;Block lettering is for the most part rectangular but occasionally adopts styling effects from Old English elements. &nbsp;Block lettering can be read universally and is considered less exclusive. &nbsp;</p>','<p>Three Dimensional Block Lettering</p>',5),(362,NULL,39,'','',6),(363,NULL,39,'','',7),(364,NULL,39,'','',8),(365,NULL,39,'','',9),(366,57,40,'<p>\"The levels of hip-hop graffiti production involve distinguishing \'writers\' who produce complex, multicolored \"pieces\" (after&nbsp;<em>masterpieces</em>), from \'taggers\' who limit their work to the simper \'tags\' (after&nbsp;<em>nametags</em>) and \'throw ups\' (they are \'thrown up\' on a wall). &nbsp;These main types of writing--tags, throw-ups, and pieces--define the hip-hop graffiti style</p>\r\n<p>Hip-hope graffiti and gang graffiti differ at a few basic levels. &nbsp;First, hip-hop graffiti has few territorial or neighborhood correlates. &nbsp;Taggers and writers take the city as their canvas as opposed to working only within the confines of their residential areas and local surroundings... Crew members may act like gang members in that they are sometimes violent towards one another. &nbsp;But they are not dirven by the context of protecting neighborhood space or themselves through the developement of a reputation. &nbsp;Their goals always relate to their art: achieving fame and respect for themselves and their crew through graffiti production.\" - Susan A. Phillips,&nbsp;<em>Wallbangin\': Graffiti and Gangs in L.A.</em></p>','',1),(367,56,40,'','',2),(368,174,40,'','',3),(369,175,40,'','',4),(370,176,40,'','',5),(371,178,40,'','',6),(372,179,40,'','',7),(373,NULL,40,'','',8),(374,NULL,40,'','',9),(375,NULL,40,'','',10),(376,NULL,40,'','',11),(377,NULL,40,'','',12),(522,NULL,36,'','',9),(521,NULL,36,'','',8),(520,NULL,36,'','',7),(519,243,36,'<p>In 1960s, the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965 gave rise to an increasing number of Thais who decided to study abroad in Los Angeles, which also led to the construction of Thai Town. Many Thai people stayed and opened businesses like Thai restaurants after they finished their study. The regional financial crisis occured in 1980s attacted even more Thais to settle in Thai Town and get a job. Around 1990s, an estimated of 80,000 Thais lived in Southern California, and on October 27, 1999, City Council designated the neighborhood.</p>\r\n<p>Thai Town was eligible for $500,000 in \"Preserve America\" grants and other public and private grants in July 2008 after Laura Bsuh, the former First Lady of the United States, granted the neighborhood recognition as a \"Preserve America\" community.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>Thai Steve Vannavong photographs his friends Chanhsamone Sysouphanh, left, and Abby Panyanouvong, during a visit to Thai Town on Hollywood Boulevard in Los Angeles</p>',6),(518,240,36,'<p>Little Tokyo from 1900s to 1910s attracted a lot of Japanese immigrants until the Exclusion Act of 1924 which limited the increasing Asian migration. Along the first street, there were shops. As for Central Avenue to the south, there were vegetables markets. Japanese American truck farms were a successful business across Southern California, so this established the status of Japanese Americans in the vegetable trade scene.</p>\r\n<p>During World War II, Little Tokyo started to declined as a great number of Japanese Americans were interned. As a result, the neighborhood attracted African Americans and Native Americans to settle in the empty properties and opened restautrants and nightclubs. The people in the nieghborhood, known as Bronzeville during the decline of Little Tokyo, moved out of the area after the internment ended.</p>\r\n<p>Japanses Americans returned from the camps and settled in the neighborhoods around downtown Los Angeles after the Second World War. They mainly stayed in apartments and boarding houses. There was a concentration of Japanese Americans in Boyle Heights which is east of Little Tokyo, in the 1950s. However, after the 1950s, they steadily moved out of Boyle Heights since more and more Mexican and Latino people immigrated and moved into that area.</p>','<p>A Little Tokyo business owner looks out onto the street on the day of the Japanese attack on Pearl Habor in Hawaii</p>',5),(517,242,36,'<p><span class=\"black\">\"Old Chinatown in its heyday, 1890 to 1910, could count 15 or so streets and alleys, and perhaps 200 building units. It had sufficient size and sophistication to boast of a Chinese opera theater, three temples, a newspaper (for a while), and later, its own telephone exchange. Old Chinatown was a residential as well as commercial community. The slow increase in the number of women would lead to the establishment of families with children. During this time, most of today\'s leading Chinese family and district associations, Chinatown institutions were founded, and church missions were organized, which began the process of community acculturation. Old Chinatown, with restaurants, curio shops, and \"strange\" entertainments, even became an attraction for the early, pioneering breed of American tourist.\"</span></p>\r\n<p><span class=\"black\">-Suellen Cheng and Munson Kwok, <em>the Los Angeles Chinatown 50th Year Guidebook</em><br /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"black\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>The balcony of a community center in Chinatown, Los Angeles, decorated with flags</p>',4),(516,241,36,'<p>From 1910 ro 1930, Mexicans steadily migrated to California, and the Mexican and Latino population in Los Angeles grown to 7.8%. Depression, severe unemployment, the possibilty of deportation and the Mexican government\'s policy triggered around 450,000 Mexican immigrants to repatriated. They were also tempted to repatriate because welfare agencies would pay for the transportation expenses for those of them who wanted to leave the United States.</p>\r\n<p>In 1931, the impact of the Mexican community was shown as Los Angeles celebrate its 150th anniversary, where there was a \"fiesta de Los Angeles\" which featured a blond \"reina\" in historic ranchera costume. The Lation population decreased to 7.1% by 1940. During World War II, discrimination against the Chicano community became severe. A local newspaper portrayed Chicano youths, who sometimes called themselves \"pachucos\" as barely civilized gangsters. In 1943\'s Zoot Suit Riots, 22 young Chicanos were almost falsely sent to prison with charge of a murder of another youth at a party in Los Angeles due to the racism of the judge conducting the trial.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>Almost 100 years ago with an increasing number of Mexican immigrants, Mexican food carts arrived on the streets near downtown Los Angeles and have continued to gain popularity ever since. Now with over 11 million Mexican-Americans living in California, it&rsquo;s no wonder that Mexican food is thriving in Los Angeles</p>',3),(515,209,36,'<p>Los Angeles has one of the largest Koreatowns in the United States. During the early 1970s, the LA Koreatown strated its development and its commercial district takes over about five-hundred block area of Los Angeles\'s mid-Wilshire, Central and Hollywood districts by early 1990.</p>\r\n<p>The first generation of the Korean American immigrant cluster has already had a well-formed internal political, cultural, and social structures. However, due to the difference in language and culture, Korean-Americans and general Americans have little contacts on the political and social aspects. Despite that, the Los Angeles Koreatown has a well blend of American and Korean institutions and a vibrantly diversed ethnic community.</p>','',2),(514,54,36,'','',1),(387,76,42,'<p>\"This tour explores the historical development of queer social communities and political movements for LGBT rights in Los Angeles. It travels through the North L.A. and Westside regions of the People\'s Guide, focusing on those neighborhoods that have been and continue to be particularly important incubators of queer social critique and political mobilization\"</p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Queer Politics and Culture Tour</h2>',1),(388,75,42,'<p>\"This tour takes you to some of the places associated with the radical social movements among people of color in L.A. during the late 1960s and the 1970s, especially the Chicano Movement, Black Power Movement, and the American Indian Movement. You\'ll spend most of your time in the Eastside and South L.A., where most Black, brown, and red people lived at that time.\"</p>','<div id=\"dublin-core-description\" class=\"element\">\r\n<div class=\"element-text\">\r\n<h2 class=\"title\">Radical People-of-Color Movements of the 1960s and \'70s Tour</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>',2),(389,74,42,'<p>\"This tour illustrates the changing nature of the Los Angeles economy in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries, as the city has transformed from a vibrant hub of high-wage, often unionized manufacturing to a site of low-wage manufacturing, high-end and low-end service work, and global circuits of multinational finance, production, labor, and migration.\"</p>\r\n<div id=\"dublin-core-description\" class=\"element\">&nbsp;</div>','<h2 class=\"title\">Economic Restructuring and Globalization Tour</h2>',3),(390,NULL,42,'','',4),(391,NULL,42,'','',5),(392,NULL,42,'','',6),(393,NULL,42,'','',7),(394,NULL,42,'','',8),(395,NULL,42,'','',9),(396,NULL,42,'','',10),(397,NULL,42,'','',11),(398,NULL,42,'','',12),(399,NULL,42,'','',13),(400,NULL,42,'','',14),(401,NULL,42,'','',15),(402,NULL,42,'','',16),(403,69,43,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Pershing Square</h2>',1),(404,73,43,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Upton Sinclair\'s House</h2>',2),(405,70,43,'<p><span>Ruben Salazar, who was an LA Times journalist instrumental in articulating Chicano struggles around the time of the Chicano Moratorium, was assassinated in the Silver Dollar Cafe by a sheriff\'s deputy\'s after just having reported on the anti-Vietnam Chicano movement in Laguna Park</span></p>','<h2 class=\"title\">Ruben Salazar Park and Silver Dollar Cafe</h2>',3),(406,NULL,43,'','',4),(407,NULL,43,'','',5),(408,NULL,43,'','',6),(409,NULL,43,'','',7),(410,NULL,43,'','',8),(411,NULL,43,'','',9),(412,NULL,43,'','',10),(413,NULL,43,'','',11),(414,NULL,43,'','',12),(415,NULL,43,'','',13),(416,NULL,43,'','',14),(417,NULL,43,'','',15),(420,163,45,'','',2),(421,165,45,'','',3),(422,167,45,'','',4),(423,NULL,45,'','',5),(424,NULL,45,'','',6),(425,NULL,45,'','',7),(426,NULL,45,'','',8),(427,NULL,45,'','',9),(440,NULL,45,'','',10),(441,NULL,45,'','',11),(442,NULL,45,'','',12),(457,137,48,'','',3),(455,142,48,'<p>Now Chicano muralism retains a few of the same goals and values as those that stemmed from \"Los Tres Grandes\" in Mexican muralist tradition after the Mexican Revolution, such as using public art as a way of conveying a politically charged question or the enforcement of an ideology. The factors that differ are the connection Latin immigrants have with their hometowns and their ability to depict them through murals as a form of nostalgia and reminicence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Further Reading:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Siqueiros and Three Early Murals in Los Angeles\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/33\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Siqueiros and Three Early Murals in Los Angeles<br /></span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a title=\"Murals in Latino Communities: Social Indicators of Community Strengths\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/37\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Murals in Latino Communities: Social Indicators of Community Strengths</span></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><br /></span></p>','',1),(456,141,48,'','',2),(443,47,47,'<p><span>The government-sponsored Bracero Program was the temporary importation of workers from Mexico to aid the American agricultural economy. This was an important historical event that many Americans are unaware of today. A bracero (from&nbsp;</span><span class=\"cite\">brazo</span><span>, the Spanish word for arm) was a Mexican worker allowed entry into the United States for a limited time, usually to work on a farm. In 1942, facing an extreme shortage of farm labor workers due to the war, Congress enacted the Emergency Labor Program. It approved the temporary immigration of thousands of Mexican workers to replace the American men who were in the armed services. During the 22 years of the Bracero Program, more than 4 million Mexican workers left their families behind and came to work in the fields of California. This migration had an enormous and lasting impact on the economy and demographics of California.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Reactions to the government program, represent the foundation upon which the later Chicano movement of the 1960s and 1970s adopted relational third world transnational identities, embracing Mexican migrant workers and other oppressed people of color while rejecting dominant American culture or whiteness. T</span><span>hey did so in ways that attempted to undermine support for the Vietnam War asserting Mexican American military service exceeded that of other groups but remained an exploitative exercise by the U.S. government.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><span>Chicanos think of themselves as living in an occupied land, invaded by Anglos. Their artwork represents this refusal to assimilate to Anglo culture. Another&nbsp;<span>key inspiration for Chicano muralists in Los Angeles is The Border, that scar that artificially separates the United States from Mexico. The Bracero program has provided a deep basis for the murals that pervade Los Angeles urban streets during the Chicano Civil Rights and Art Movements.&nbsp;<span>Production of The Great Wall of Los Angeles aligned perfectly with the changing demographics in the San Fernando Valley.&nbsp;</span><span>Panels depicting the likes of baby boomers and braceros offer a glimpse into personal struggles and achievements that are otherwise unheralded. Those with the good fortune to live near the wall can appreciate it as a constant reminder of their own place in history.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Further resources:</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/show/48\">Bracero History Archive</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(444,133,47,'','',2),(445,131,47,'','',3),(446,134,47,'','',4),(447,132,47,'','',5),(448,48,47,'','',6),(449,166,47,'','',7),(450,116,47,'','',8),(451,NULL,47,'','',9),(452,NULL,47,'','',10),(453,NULL,47,'','',11),(454,NULL,47,'','