INSERT INTO `omeka_sections` VALUES (12,'I. Riots','<p>Riots occur for myriad reasons. Furthermore, the articulation of these very reasons are highly politicized. What is given in this section is not so much a critical analysis of cause, but a brief survey of three major riots that have highly impacted Los Angeles\' urban environment. These include the \'65 Watts Riots, the wartime Zootsuit Riots, and the \'92 L.A. Riots.</p>',3,1,'riots'),(13,'II. Community Organizing','<p>Community organizing is one of the most fundamentally democratic modes of effecting change. Here, two examples are given of this: the Chicano Moratorium in the early 1970\'s and a local (and contemporary) offshoot of Occupy Wall Street, Occupy UCLA.&nbsp;</p>',3,2,'comm--organizing'),(14,'III. Radical Politics: Tours and Landmarks','<p>This section offers a generous survey of radical political activity that has gone on in Los Angeles, and put it into map form so that you can easily experience these places for yourself. Themes include Queer Politics and Culture, People-of-Color movements of the \'60s and \'70s, and a tour covering crucial sites of Economic Restructuring and Globalization. Other political landmarks are also given, such as Upton Sinclair\'s house and Pershing Square.</p>',3,3,'tours--radical-politics'),(18,'I. Chicano History','<p><span>For many years the Chicano people were considered the silent or forgotten minority, or referred to anonymously as one of the other oppressed nationalities. The plight of Chicanos as an oppressed people was not in the public spotlight. In Los Angeles, the Chicano people faced a particularly difficult struggle with local authorities and other communities.</span></p>',8,1,'chicano-history'),(19,'II. Murals','<p><span>As Mexican artists began to actively participate in the efforts to address issues of cultural heritage and belonging in the United States, there emerged a new iconography and symbolic language which not only articulated the movement, but became the core of a Chicano cultural renaissance.</span></p>',8,2,'-murals-'),(20,'III. Beautification Policy','<p><span>The movement to \"beautify\" Los Angeles through the use of certain aspects of street art and muralism in order to attract tourism and improve the overall aesthetic appeal of Los Angeles.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>This section includes information on zoning, policy, and the changing attitudes of murals as art in a comprehensive look at the role that muralism plays as a form of public art today.&nbsp;</p>',8,3,'urban-beautification-policy'),(21,'I. Signage','<p>The booming of commercial businesses, especially the entertainment industry, led to a prosperous development of hotels and theaters in their heyday. Tycoons from big companies and the entertainment industry used outdoor adversting as a mean for promotion. This gave rise to a vibrant visualization of Los Angeles, but at the same time, it also caused public nuisance. Lastly, multilingual sinage can be seen everywhere in Los Angeles, which reflects the cultural diversity of the city. At a deeper level, one can relate this to the migration history of people around the world to Los Angeles.</p>',10,1,'evolution-of-la'),(22,'II. Graffiti ','<p>Graffiti as Signage, Typography, and Style</p>',10,2,'urban-and-colloquial-signage');
