INSERT INTO `omeka_simple_pages_pages` VALUES (1,7,1,1,1,'About','about','<p>This repository is centered on the street life and history of Los Angeles through the lens of the visual culture many take for granted. It covers a broad spectrum, which gives us leeway in attacking several different issues, such as race relational history, politics, social struggles of different minorities (including the Chicano peoples), and commercialization\'s contribution to the visual culture. We hope to help define what the street life of Los Angeles is like and how what you see among the streets contributes to the its culture and lifestyle. Due to things like immigration, riots, and art, Los Angeles has a diverse community that is elusive in connotation. Young UCLA students do not really have a clear idea of what downtown LA is really about or what it has to offer. Many people are misguided that downtown is just a &ldquo;ghetto&rdquo; and does not have much to offer. This project will create a repository for giving downtown and the greater Los Angeles area a hisotrical background in the context of its visual culture. Urban Los Angeles could be defined and expressed in infinite ways and we are here to give a sense of meaning from a college student&rsquo;s perspective. The city has had many influences in areas from commercial to racial that are hidden behind many of its murals, signages, and street art. We want to expose that history by portraying the city&rsquo;s visual culture. By taking this spin on urban Los Angeles, we will have provided a unique outlook to the street life and culture of the &ldquo;City of Angels&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Browse by...</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=graffiti\"><img src=\"http://i45.tinypic.com/2cxavs5.jpg\" alt=\"\" /><br /></a><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=Murals\"><br /><img src=\"http://i47.tinypic.com/w0pdv4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"301\" height=\"30\" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=signage\"><img src=\"http://i48.tinypic.com/2ebv2pw.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a><br /><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=signage\"><br /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=Street+art\"><img src=\"http://i45.tinypic.com/9sgsoi.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>','2012-11-22 22:48:55','2012-10-19 17:19:37',0,0,'',1),(2,7,4,1,1,'How To Navigate Our Site','navigate','<center><a href=\"http://picasion.com/\"><img src=\"http://i.picasion.com/pic60/baedb09589ec604dc449a77074e1a26e.gif\" alt=\"free gif maker\" width=\"400\" height=\"318\" border=\"0\" /></a></center>\r\n<p>This site is designed to carry you through the different aspects that we believe distinguish urban and street Los Angeles from most other cities and neighborhoods in the area. Urban Los Angeles has a long history made up of conflict, blood shed, layout planning, art, and commercialization, and we wanted to point to users to these areas and create a narrative. The About page has links to items tagged with \"Graffiti,\" \"Community Murals,\" \"Signage,\" and \"Street Art\". These four sections make up the main categories that define the visual culture of each area in LA.</p>\r\n<p>Once users explore these areas, they can familiarize themselves with what we have considered are the parameters for each category and what necessarily defines what each one means. On the left hand menu, the user is then able to view our exhibits, each of which explains why each category seen on the homepage contributes to the visual culture and its significance. Murals in LA, for example, are explained as a visual expression of the Chicano history in LA. Street art is often an expression of political protests and riots that have occured in the past--a symbol of social and political struggles as well. Signage and typography are more looked-over aspects of visual culture often seen as LA became more commercialized and gangs became more defined and prominent. Typography and signage can often convey powerful messages and have hidden or unconscious meanings that portray the creator\'s intentions.</p>\r\n<p>We hope that this repository as a whole will provide the user with a story of urban Los Angeles\' history and give a comprehensive description of the visual makeup of a city that has an immense amount of character and personality more than often expressed through what you see with your eyes.</p>\r\n<p>Browse by&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=Graffiti\">graffiti</a>, <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse/tag/murals\">community murals</a>, <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse/tag/signage\">signage</a>, or <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab3/items/browse?tags=Street+art\">street art</a></p>','2012-12-07 04:28:29','2012-11-12 20:34:53',2,0,'',1),(3,4,7,1,1,'Survey Visualizations','survey-visualizations','<p>We asked 100 current students at UCLA from each grade level (1st year through graduate level) over a one month period. Questions regarded Downtown Los Angeles and asked where the respondent has been within downtown and how they felt about downtown in terms of cleanliness and pace. Below are visualizations created from our data once filtered by year or type of environment the respondent is from (rural, suburban, urban). Our goal was to find some connections between age/home environment and how they perceive the visualizations around them in LA.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Please hold control (command for macs) + click title of the visualization to view in its entirety.</strong></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://www-958.ibm.com/me/visualizations/91cb283839f211e28f2b000255111976/comments/91ce254239f211e28f2b000255111976.js?width=425&amp;height=350\"></script>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Originally, we hypothesized that as year in school increased, the more number of places the student would visit. However, our data shows that 1st years had the 2nd to highest average of places visited next to 4th years. 2nd, 3rd, and 4th years followed our hypothesis with an increasing average number of areas visited. Perhaps this year\'s freshman class was very exploratory.<br />\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://www-958.ibm.com/me/visualizations/d4f82750382611e2a80f000255111976/comments/d50bc9e0382611e2a80f000255111976.js?width=425&amp;height=350\"></script>\r\n</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">From these graphs the only pattern we noticed is that the second years tended to have the highest percentage of visitors to the most number of areas downtown. There was not a clear relationship between year and type of area visited. We did, however, find that lower classmen (1st &amp; 2nd years) visited union station more often than older classmen (3rd and 4th years) perhaps because of a lack of transportation (no car at college yet), as well as the civic center, which is central to many tourist areas like Chinatown and Little Tokyo. A higher percentage of upperclassmen visited Skid Row, Jewelry District, and Warehouse District--all areas that are more or less appealing to the mass public as tourist spots. <br />\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://www-958.ibm.com/me/visualizations/e1776eb6382911e295a8000255111976/comments/e17ae794382911e295a8000255111976.js?width=425&amp;height=350\"></script>\r\n</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Notice that those from rural areas tended to see downtown LA as primarily<em> exciting, hectic, and safe</em>. Those from suburban areas tended to see it as primarily <em>exciting, hectic, and dirty</em>. Those from urban areas tended to see it as <em>exciting, hectic, dirty, and dangerous. </em>This is an interesting find because we can formulate the proposal that rural students come from less developed area and find DTLA more exciting and safe because they have not been exposed to such a new metropolitan type of area. Suburban students are used to uniform housing and safe, clean areas so they find DTLA exciting but dirty. Urban students are used to the DTLA type of environment but still see it as exciting, hectic, dirty, and dangerous.Perhaps they see through some of the excitement and notice its less appealing aspects.<em><br /> </em><br />\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://www-958.ibm.com/me/visualizations/cb317f3a390411e2832c000255111976/comments/cb346240390411e2832c000255111976.js?width=425&amp;height=350\"></script>\r\n</p>\r\n</center><center><img src=\"http://i1296.photobucket.com/albums/ag17/Argeyen/LAgraph1.png\" alt=\"LA Visualization\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></center>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The question we posed in the survey for the two graphs pictured above (\"Visual Culture of Los Angeles: Who Pays Attention to What?\") was, \"Which do you pay attention to most when walking/driving around? (downtown or elsewhere in LA).\" They could choose more than one option for the categories we gave them, which were: historical architecture, storefronts, cleanliness/hospitality, urban design, ads, tagging, murals, and graffiti. We decided to examine their responses by the areas they were from to see if there was a difference between where people were from and what aspects of visual culture they noticed in a very urban area. The graphs show that the top three things students who originated from rural areas pay attention to are historical architecture, murals, and graffiti. In suburban areas it was storefronts, historical architecture, and graffiti, while those from urban areas noticed storefronts, cleanliness, and historical architecture. In effect, those from rural areas were more attracted to visual aspects of an urban environment than functional (compared to those from urban areas).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>What\'s the difference between the two graphs?&nbsp;The Many Eyes rendition of \"Visual Culture of Los Angeles: Who Pays Attention to What?\" is more interactive, however lacking in the ability to compare each of the three visuals created (rural, suburban, urban) next to each other. Thus, we felt it was necessary to create another graph on Excel to create a more clear picture of the relationships demonstrated. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Some difficulties we faced include the limitations of accuracy due to a small sample size (100 students total and only about 20-25 students from each grade level). This means that the generalizations we are making from these visualizations must be considered with caution. We also learned that we should have also asked respondents which city they were from specifically to get a better idea of how their background might have affected their visual perceptions so we did not have to rely on as many assumptions. Additionally, the interactivity promoted by Many Eyes downplayed the relationships created between subjects and variables in the data.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2012-11-30 05:52:05','2012-11-27 07:57:13',0,0,'',1),(4,7,7,1,0,'Community Murals Map','community-murals-map','<p><strong>Hispanic Communities and Muralism in Los Angeles</strong></p>\r\n<p>Below is a GIS map of the 2000 Los Angeles Census data of the Hispanic population in each district. The top layer displays the murals created during the Neighborhood Pride Mural Program.</p>\r\n<p>\"Judy Baca and SPARC undertook the task of creating and implementing Great Walls Unlimited: Neighborhood Pride. Beginning in 1988, the program has since produced 105 murals in almost every ethnic community of Los Angeles. Over its fourteen-year history Great Walls Unlimited: Neighborhood Pride has employed over 90 different established and emerging muralists from Los Angeles and around the country, trained hundreds of youth apprentices, collaborated with countless community based organizations, worked closely with the fifteen different Council Districts that make up the City of Los Angeles.\" (<a href=\"http://www.sparcmurals.org/sparcone/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=43&amp;Itemid=75\">website</a>)</p>\r\n<p>We chose the murals most related to the Hispanic community in hopes of finding a relationship between these murals location and where the Hispanic communities were most populated. We used the SPARC Neighborhood Pride project murals to locate points of community and civic engagement important in developing communities, and decided to overlay it with census data on Hispanic population within Los Angeles as muralism is deeply rooted in Chicano/Mexican American history.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<center><iframe src=\"http://geocommons.com/maps/216129/embed\" width=\"150%\" height=\"700\"></iframe></center>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Above we can see that the Hispanic communities are most populated in East Los Angeles. However, these related murals are located mostly in downtown and South Central Los Angeles. We believe that perhaps these muralists placed these murals here due to restraints from City Council Districts. Regardless, these areas are still more populated by Hispanics than the surrounding areas to the West, still leaving an impact of cultural pride. Still surronding the highly dense Hispanic areas, these community murals in LA can still be considered to be indebted to the Chicana/o movement. And since it is neighboring these areas, the influence of Chicana/o murals of the 60/70\'s actually extends beyond the most concentrated Hispanic neighborhoods.These murals also stand as an effort to beautify these areas, especially with the high visibility the downtown area brings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Credit: Stephanie Wong &amp; Leslie Bloomfield</em></p>','2012-12-06 02:38:53','2012-11-29 06:03:37',0,0,'',1),(5,4,4,1,0,'Methodology & Challenges','methodology--challenges','<p><strong>Methodology - Developing our Topic:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong>&nbsp;Our project examines the visual culture of Los Angeles through different mediums, specifically graffiti, murals, street art, and signage. Initially we started the quarter with divergent ideas--each of us individually had our own idea of what the scope of the project should be. While Rachael, Matt, and Leslie wanted to focus on street art and graffiti, Ryan was looking more towards housing and urban development in Los Angeles. Stephanie, on the other hand, wanted to research political and historical events relating mostly to racial dynamics in the 20th century, and Ashley was interested in commercial buildings. Our beginning idea was housing policy in LA in relation to visual communication, but we struggled to connect our distinct ideas. Over the course of the quarter we collectively had a lot of materials and digital objects, but had yet to overcome the struggle in creating a narrative that related all of our interests. In the wide scope of urban planning in Los Angeles and street art, we worked to narrow the definitions of what was important to our narrative. Over the course of the quarter through working on the project and conducting research we eventually converged on the theme of dynamics of urban housing and visual culture in Los Angeles.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Digital Tools &amp; Limitations:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Omeka</span>: We generally found Omeka not efficient in the uploading and organization of our digital objects, and found the interface counter-intuitive and not very versatile. It was also difficult to see the different sections and pages in our exhibits as separated and ordered. So we found it helpful to add hierarchial markers to make the order and sections more clear and visible (ex: I. Chicano History II. Murals III. Beautification Policy). The layout options for the pages within the exhibits was also very limited. If you did not have the exact amount of items that fit the layout models, the page would look offset.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Material</span>: The temporality of visual culture made it hard to find physical documentation of subjects such as graffiti and signage. However, found images through books including a dissertation from a UCLA graduate student. Google Scholar and the UCLA digital library were also great resources in helping to find information.</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Neatline</span>: Posted 23 essential events that happened during the 1992 riots, and through data-mining found a repository of all deaths that were a result of the riots. Placed these in the context of a map that connected social unrest with deaths that occurred. Some challenges faced were that events disappeared, descriptions inconsistent in showing up, default on map is zoomed in, couldn\'t include timeline to correlate to hours a dates, and unable to put a specific address in - had to eyeball a point on the map to mark a particular event.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Geocommons</span>: Had many difficulties with the data uploading correctly. Layers also would refuse to save when rearranged. These are bugs that the platform is responsible for.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">esurveycreator.com</span>: Unclear wording and misrepresentation of services offered for free created a difficulty in accessing the data we gathered. Had to eventually pay to acquire the rest of the data.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Many Eyes</span>: Our primary source of data visualizations came from Many Eyes. Our choice in using Many Eyes stemmed from its ability to create interactive media-based visualizations. However, after working on this platform, it became clear that they had a specific and limiting outline for what kind of data you could input and how it was formatted. Therefore, we were unable to fully gain a comprehensive analysis of our data.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Division of Tasks:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Leslie - Omeka interface, graffiti, signage, Geocommons&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Matt - Riots (Zoot Suit, 1965 riots, 1992 riots, Election 2012), Street Art, Neatline&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Ryan - Protests, Riots and its Presentations (Radical politics: political tours, and Landmarks, Community Organizing), Neatline&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Yee - Signage (hotels, theaters, billboards, multilingual)&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Stephanie - Geocommons, Murals (Chicano history), survey, data visualizations</li>\r\n<li>Rachael - Murals Exhibit, Beautification Exhibit, survey, data visualizations</li>\r\n</ul>','2012-12-07 07:10:49','2012-11-30 02:18:25',0,0,'',1);
